  "translated_text": "-- The livelihood sector is where ordinary people struggle in their daily lives. For citizens, the most pressing issues are how much their children's school fees will increase and what housing prices are like. According to a survey conducted November 21-22 targeting 1,000 adult men and women nationwide regarding the most urgent livelihood issues the president should address, the results were: 4th place - reducing educational cost burden (12.4%), 3rd place - stabilizing real estate including housing prices (12.6%), 2nd place - stabilizing prices including oil prices (24.9%), 1st place - resolving unemployment through job creation (33.6%). The president seems to have set next year's economic growth forecast at 4-5%, and the Korea Development Institute projects 5.5%. Economic indicators are improving, but ordinary people don't feel it. When might the economic sentiment improve for ordinary citizens? ▲I'm thinking a lot about this exact point. Economic growth is recovering fastest among OECD [Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development] countries right now, and it's expected to be the highest next year as well, so the IMF [International Monetary Fund] and OECD say it will be 4.5%. I expect it will be revised slightly upward by year-end. I think next year's economy will be around 5%. However, looking at various indicators, some say we need exit strategies, but I disagree. Even though our economic numbers look good and we're leading among OECD countries, there are many variables in the global economy. Problems arose in Dubai, and if any developed country experiences a financial crisis, the ripple effects will reach us immediately. If the global economy weakens, we won't be able to sell our products. We can't predict how much oil and gas prices will rise. They say oil prices will be around $80 next year, but I think they'll go up to $100. External forecasts also suggest around 5%. Companies and small businesses feel it first. For ordinary people's sentiment, it will probably take until the first half of next year. In the first half, we'll restart the so-called Hope Work projects from February and resume internships. Youth unemployment is slightly over 8% now. In the US and Europe, it's nearly 20%. While we're better than developed countries, the government's immediate task is how to create jobs. When the economic growth rate improves, corporate investment will begin, and domestic demand is recovering somewhat faster than the government predicted, so things will probably improve somewhat. But the government is focusing on leading the creation of good jobs among ordinary people's measures and job creation. Because small businesses can't find 200,000 people. How do we match job seekers with employers? When there's a mismatch, the government is making specific plans for retraining and customized training. Since we've become a country that provides aid, when we transfer our experience overseas, 20,000 young people will go abroad annually. We're focusing support on small businesses and startups. Because of the government's efforts to create opportunities for young people, people will be able to feel the effects in the second half. [Image enlargement] -- You said the economy will smoothly reach about 5% growth next year and recovered quickly without major damage compared to the global financial crisis, but many question whether our economy's fundamentals are recovering. I understand there are many concerns about side effects if we rely on short-term stimulus without fundamental improvements. What's your perspective? ▲In fact, through the first half and third quarter, we've relied heavily on government fiscal spending. To continue growing, private corporate investment must follow. That's how demand is created. I was very worried entering the fourth quarter. We thought it would go into negative growth, but fortunately it was positive growth. Looking at the content, private investment began much better than we worried about in the third quarter, and private consumption is also increasing slightly. Because household savings are very weak, there's an issue with savings. Can companies continue to activate investment in the fourth quarter? Companies must see investment value - they don't invest just because the government tells them to. Listening to business groups, companies were passive about investment in the second quarter but are being proactive by the end of the fourth quarter. We're closely monitoring fundamentals, private investment, consumption, savings, etc. Foreign countries evaluate Korea as doing well. By 2014-2015, fiscal deficits will reverse and become surpluses. The government is monitoring very closely and hasn't disbanded the emergency economic response committee yet. Our view is that exit measures should be implemented more slowly. [Image enlargement] -- What you did well was hosting the G20 summit, and what you did poorly was tax cuts for the rich. ▲Since becoming president, I'm misunderstood as being pro-big business and pro-rich, but ultimately, I'm instinctively not that way. Big companies must do well to create jobs. You could say I'm pro-market, but I'm pro-jobs. Tax cuts create jobs. 65% of tax cut benefits go to small businesses. Calling this policy for the rich is a misunderstanding. It's frustrating, but I have firm convictions. (Tax cuts) create jobs and stimulate domestic demand, I believe. -- You mentioned the MISO Foundation as an example of pro-ordinary people policy, but there are concerns about moral hazard if people just take money without doing business and don't repay. ▲While this is part of ordinary people's policy, those suffering most are traditional market vendors and street vendors - these people can't access financial services. This doesn't apply to small business owners; street vendors don't get proper benefits. When urgent, they use private loans of 1 million won [approximately $760 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] and it grows to 10 times the principal. The foreign term is microcredit. We called it MISO because we liked the name. Large corporations and financial institutions voluntarily contributed 1.3 trillion won [approximately $990 million USD] and companies do it themselves. Each company contributes a certain amount, providing as little as 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD], 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD], up to 10 million won [approximately $7,600 USD] in some places. We haven't been doing this long, but many people say the intent is good but ask about moral hazard. Two weeks ago at an event, an elderly woman wanted to meet me, but security wouldn't allow it, so I brought her over. She was making fish-shaped pastries in Jongno but couldn't continue because she lacked 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD]. She borrowed 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD] to make fish-shaped pastries again and came to thank me. She said she'd only used private loans her whole life - this was her first time getting low-interest financing. She said what she wants to do now is give fish-shaped pastries to poor people who could only watch without being able to buy them in the past, since she received the nation's help. I was moved. I tell people who talk about moral hazard: People who borrow 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] will never default. They might repay late, but they'll repay. However, people who take 5 billion won [approximately $3.8 million USD] or 10 billion won [approximately $7.6 million USD] sometimes default. I'm confident that people who borrow 3-5 million won [approximately $2,280-3,800 USD] will repay, so this system should be expanded. Participating companies and financial institutions have 700-800 billion won [approximately $530-610 million USD] remaining, so we'll probably create nearly 2 trillion won [approximately $1.5 billion USD] in MISO financing for loans. [Image enlargement] -- What you did well was hosting the G20 summit, and what you did poorly was tax cuts for the rich. ▲Since becoming president, I'm misunderstood as being pro-big business and pro-rich, but ultimately, I'm instinctively not that way. Big companies must do well to create jobs. You could say I'm pro-market, but I'm pro-jobs. Tax cuts create jobs. 65% of tax cut benefits go to small businesses. Calling this policy for the rich is a misunderstanding. It's frustrating, but I have firm convictions. (Tax cuts) create jobs and stimulate domestic demand, I believe. -- You mentioned the MISO Foundation as an example of pro-ordinary people policy, but there are concerns about moral hazard if people just take money without doing business and don't repay. ▲While this is part of ordinary people's policy, those suffering most are traditional market vendors and street vendors - these people can't access financial services. This doesn't apply to small business owners; street vendors don't get proper benefits. When urgent, they use private loans of 1 million won [approximately $760 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] and it grows to 10 times the principal. The foreign term is microcredit. We called it MISO because we liked the name. Large corporations and financial institutions voluntarily contributed 1.3 trillion won [approximately $990 million USD] and companies do it themselves. Each company contributes a certain amount, providing as little as 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD], 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD], up to 10 million won [approximately $7,600 USD] in some places. We haven't been doing this long, but many people say the intent is good but ask about moral hazard. Two weeks ago at an event, an elderly woman wanted to meet me, but security wouldn't allow it, so I brought her over. She was making fish-shaped pastries in Jongno but couldn't continue because she lacked 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD]. She borrowed 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD] to make fish-shaped pastries again and came to thank me. She said she'd only used private loans her whole life - this was her first time getting low-interest financing. She said what she wants to do now is give fish-shaped pastries to poor people who could only watch without being able to buy them in the past, since she received the nation's help. I was moved. I tell people who talk about moral hazard: People who borrow 3 million won [approximately $2,280 USD] or 5 million won [approximately $3,800 USD] will never default. They might repay late, but they'll repay. However, people who take 5 billion won [approximately $3.8 million USD] or 10 billion won [approximately $7.6 million USD] sometimes default. I'm confident that people who borrow 3-5 million won [approximately $2,280-3,800 USD] will repay, so this system should be expanded. Participating companies and financial institutions have 700-800 billion won [approximately $530-610 million USD] remaining, so we'll probably create nearly 2 trillion won [approximately $1.5 billion USD] in MISO financing for loans. [Image enlargement] -- (Citizen) I'm approaching graduation and trying hard to find employment, but it's difficult. You mentioned venture startups to resolve youth unemployment, but startups realistically have few success stories and are difficult. The reality is that the income, welfare, and standards we hope for fall short, so rather than just telling us to lower our expectations, wouldn't it be right to present fundamental solutions? ▲Many people say to lower expectations, but I don't use those words. I felt bad when I heard that when I was young. Don't lower them, match them. Going to big companies often means doing predetermined work and repeating the same tasks. Small businesses might be disappointing, but the scope is broader with more to experience. They hire new employees but nowadays they all hire experienced workers. In such cases, you can gain experience at small businesses and move to other companies. Small business owners say salaries are decent but young people don't apply. Many young people's majors don't match, so the government provides education for that. There are 6-month to 1-year courses nationwide where you can receive free education with 600,000-1 million won [approximately $460-760 USD] support. Ventures literally require taking challenges. You might fail, but don't fear failure. If you fear failure and do nothing, you can't gain experience. Through failure, you can also gain experience and mature. I actually joined a small company. That small company later became a large company, but people asked why I was going to such a company. Still, I found fulfillment at the small company and experienced growing as the company grew. I'm saying to look at small companies too. Aren't service industries good jobs? 40-50 are created, but manufacturing creates less than 10. We'll foster service industries so many young people can enter them. -- I'm a company employee in my 30s. I tried to apply for special sales of Bogeumjari housing for newlyweds, but couldn't apply because I don't have children. Friends also give up applications due to strict conditions. You emphasize residential stability for ordinary people - could you provide comprehensive measures for ordinary people? ▲After getting married, I moved 8 times in 3 years. I was kicked out every 6 months. Later I went to a 20-pyeong [approximately 660 sq ft] apartment and had four children. I promised to create long-term rental and sales apartments that can be used for 10-20+ years near downtown, close to workplaces, and give priority to people who worked their whole lives but couldn't own homes, even if they're not newlyweds. When trying to implement the policy, suddenly many people got married and many newlyweds appeared, making it unmanageable. But I can't investigate pregnancies. We're taking measures to accommodate people who say they're pregnant, and Bogeumjari housing doesn't come out just once but twice a year. The government is considering giving the same opportunities to those who are definitely pregnant. But speculation and selling shouldn't happen. Since they're very cheap, new green buildings with low management costs and high-quality construction, I hope there's no speculation. [Image enlargement] -- In the past, there were many kidnappings so parents worried a lot. Now with the 'Cho Doo-soon case' and others, parents with daughters are uneasy. As parents, we worry about preventing repeat offenses and whether we can safely send children outside. ▲It's truly bewildering. We talk about becoming a first-class nation and developed country, but you don't become developed just by increasing income. You become developed when things like child sex crimes disappear and people can live comfortably. Among all crimes, I think child sex crimes are the most immoral. Child sex offenders should be isolated from society for life. In our country, sentences for drug offenders and child sex offenders are lower than in other developed countries. We should raise these and establish government measures so wherever these people move, everyone knows what kind of people they are, making it impossible for them to establish themselves. We should eliminate such heinous criminals and create 'caregivers' for children going to school, where neighborhood grandmothers take them and mothers with time take turns caring for other children and their own. -- My ideal type is a woman who cooks well. While watching TV, I saw news on American CNN where First Lady Kim Yoon-ok introduced our food. Does First Lady Kim actually cook well, and does the president occasionally cook too? ▲I don't cook well. I haven't had opportunities to cook, but I make good ramen. My wife is probably watching TV now. I should say she cooks well - what good would it do to say she doesn't? My wife makes excellent chicken gangjeong. She's interested in cooking, but following the Korean Wave, let's spread Korean food globally as healthy food, so the Korean Wave spreads food culture along with arts and culture. -- One of my children is a university student but went as a police auxiliary, which was a relief, but during middle and high school, I thought my back would break from hagwon education [private tutoring] costs. They say if you don't go into debt in middle school, you're fortunate. Every time the president announces hagwon education cost reduction measures, there's the strange phenomenon of hagwon education costs rising. Are there hagwon education cost reduction measures? ▲Education can be called Korea's chronic disease. For 30 years, we've talked about equalized education, but people still send children to hagwon education because university admissions can't be equalized, so people have no choice but to receive hagwon education. The university admission system must change. Shouldn't it disappear if we say you can get in without receiving hagwon education? Instead of selecting by grades, if someone scores 90 with hagwon education and someone scores 80 without hagwon education, the university should accept the 80-point scorer. This evaluates that if this person had received hagwon education, they would have scored more than 90 - they have potential. It's comprehensive evaluation including how well they cooperate with friends, social awareness, family awareness, etc. When Korean students apply to top American universities, don't they evaluate by sending records? Now several universities like KAIST and POSTECH select 100% through admissions officers' interviews. Since Seoul National University and all universities are gradually using admissions officers, don't just study. You can't adapt in the world by just memorizing and cramming like before. You need creativity. You need the ability to cooperate with others and leadership. Elementary and secondary education should also be more free, not focused on memorization and grades. Children should be healthy and play sports too. Reviving public education has been discussed for a long time. School grades are announced, aren't they? Teachers also have good and bad teachers who continue as is, but now let's evaluate teachers too. Let inadequate teachers receive retraining. That's how public education can be revived. For truly necessary hagwon education and supplementary lessons, we must completely transform EBS [Educational Broadcasting System, Korea's state-run educational media] to the same level as going to top hagwons. Many people already use it. We're really trying to change things. -- Are you healthy? I wear long underwear in cold winter. I heard the president also wears long underwear - it's not because you're cold like me, right? ▲Once I started wearing it, it became a habit and it's good. Green growth isn't grandiose - just think about what each citizen can do. By wearing long underwear, the Blue House temperature dropped 3 degrees. Energy was reduced 20% and 2 trillion won [approximately $1.5 billion USD] was saved. Carbon emissions also decreased. No other country in the world takes off clothes at home like ours. I hope Korea does this too from the perspective of carbon emission reduction and energy conservation. I can't tell others to wear it, so only I wear it. So naturally the Blue House wears it too."
}
